Bonus: GradientShop

  • I implement the sharpening filter to the two images.
  • I only utilize the gradient values (the difference between the adjacent pixels).
  • Basic logic of process is similar to the "AI621_20225421_penguin" and "AI621_20225421_toy"
  • The difference is that the gradient is multiplied by scalar(>1) for sharpening.
  • This sharpening factor can be a constant value (simple sharpening), or a variable obtained by a expression (robust weighting scheme)

Load image

girl = imresize(im2double(imread('./data/custom/girl_pearl.jpeg')), 0.5, 'bilinear');
harry = imresize(im2double(imread('./data/custom/harry.png')), 0.5, 'bilinear');

Simple sharpening

  • For simple sharpening I use the sharpening factor 5
sharp_girl = simple_sharp(girl,5);
imwrite(sharp_girl,'simple_sharp_girl.png');
sharp_harry = simple_sharp(harry,5);
imwrite(sharp_harry,'simple_sharp_harry.png');

Robust Weighting scheme

  • Like the simple method, if only gradient values are scaled up, the corresponding color contrast may increase or unwanted noise may occur.
  • To prepare for this, robust weightening multiplies the weight with the sharpening factor, which regularize the outliers of gradient are not generated well.
  • For robust weigting scheme, I use the sharpening factor as 10 and b=5 for w_x and w_y.
r_sharp_girl = robust_sharp(girl,5,10);
imwrite(r_sharp_girl,'robust_sharp_girl.png');
r_sharp_harry = robust_sharp(harry,5,10);
imwrite(r_sharp_harry,'robust_sharp_harry.png');
Above are the results of two sharpening methods.
  • It can be seen that the edge is more emphasized than original image when both images are sharpened in each method.
  • From the perspective of the intensity of the sharpening, the simple sharpening method is much more intuitive, but this method has created a lot of noise.
  • On the other hand, while using robust weightening reduces the magnitude of sharpening, unnecessary edges such as noise on the girl's face do not get larger, and it can be seen that the edge is emphasized a little more in necessary areas such as wrinkles and hair.
In conclusion, both methods have advantages and disadvantages, but they do well in sharpening effectively.
function [output] = simple_sharp(img,cs)
 
[imh, imw, nn] = size(img);
im2var = zeros(imh, imw);
im2var(1:imh*imw) = 1:imh*imw;
 
nrow = imh*imw;
ncol = (imw-1)*imh+imw*(imh-1)+1+imw*imh;
A = sparse([], [], [], ncol, nrow, 0);
b = sparse(ncol,1);
output = zeros(imh,imw,nn);
 
for z = 1:nn
e = 0;
s = img(:,:,z);
for y = 1:imh
for x = 1:imw-1
e = e+1;
A(e, im2var(y,x+1)) = 1;
A(e,im2var(y,x)) = -1;
b(e) = cs*(s(y,x+1) - s(y,x));
end
end
for x = 1:imw
for y = 1:imh-1
e = e+1;
A(e, im2var(y+1,x)) = 1;
A(e,im2var(y,x)) = -1;
b(e) = cs*(s(y+1,x) - s(y,x));
end
end
for x = 1:imw
for y = 1:imh
e = e+1;
A(e,im2var(y,x)) = 1;
b(e) = s(y,x);
end
end
 
v = A\b;
 
n=0;
for j = 1:imw
for i = 1:imh
n = n+1;
output(i,j,z) = v(n);
end
end
end
end
 
function [output] = robust_sharp(img,B,cs)
 
[imh, imw, nn] = size(img);
im2var = zeros(imh, imw);
im2var(1:imh*imw) = 1:imh*imw;
 
nrow = imh*imw;
ncol = (imw-1)*imh+imw*(imh-1)+1+imw*imh;
A = sparse([], [], [], ncol, nrow, 0);
b = sparse(ncol,1);
output = zeros(imh,imw,nn);
 
for z = 1:nn
e = 0;
s = img(:,:,z);
for y = 1:imh
for x = 1:imw-1
e = e+1;
A(e, im2var(y,x+1)) = 1;
A(e,im2var(y,x)) = -1;
wx = (abs(2*s(y,x)-s(y,x+1))+1).^(-B);
b(e) = wx*cs*(s(y,x+1) - s(y,x));
end
end
for x = 1:imw
for y = 1:imh-1
e = e+1;
A(e, im2var(y+1,x)) = 1;
A(e,im2var(y,x)) = -1;
wy = (abs(s(y,x)*2-s(y+1,x))+1).^(-B);
b(e) = wy*cs*(s(y+1,x) - s(y,x));
end
end
for x = 1:imw
for y = 1:imh
e = e+1;
A(e,im2var(y,x)) = 1;
b(e) = s(y,x);
end
end
 
v = A\b;
 
n=0;
for j = 1:imw
for i = 1:imh
n = n+1;
output(i,j,z) = v(n);
end
end
end
end
